</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="12" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,779,1094]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,419,779,805]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Diagnostic characters:</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Leach" authorityYear="1815" box="[426,513,779,805]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="99" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Arctiini">Arctiini</taxonomicName>
are mainly defined by an elongated retinaculum in males (reduced or shortened in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Billberg" authorityYear="1820" box="[151,263,815,841]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="99" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Lithosiini">Lithosiini</taxonomicName>
, or absent in Syntominae), a homoplastic character, and heteroideous crochets (Kitching &amp; Rawlins in 
<bibRefCitation author="Kristensen, N. P." box="[151,365,851,877]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" pagination="237 - 253" refId="ref69263" refString="Kristensen, N. P. (1999) Phylogeny of endopterygote insects, the most successful lineage of living organisms. European Journal of Entomology, 96, 237 - 253." type="journal article" year="1999">Kristensen (1999))</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="12" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,779,1094]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,520,887,913]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Diversity and distribution:</emphasis>
In 
<collectingCountry box="[559,619,887,913]" name="India" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">India</collectingCountry>
, tribe 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Leach" authorityYear="1815" box="[689,776,887,913]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Arctiini">Arctiini</taxonomicName>
comprises a total of 180 species and two subspecies in 38 genera. Of the 38 genera, 12 are represented by single species, 24 genera by two to 20 species and two genera, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Butler" authorityYear="1875" box="[151,260,959,985]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Spilarctia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,260,959,985]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Spilarctia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Walker, 1856:" authorityYear="1690" box="[314,400,960,985]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Lemyra" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[314,400,960,985]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Lemyra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are represented by 21 and 42 species, respectively (
<figureCitation box="[979,1049,959,985]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="11.[151,250,2014,2038]" captionTargetBox="[157,1422,1128,1970]" captionTargetId="figure-344@11.[151,1436,1115,1989]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 4. Species diversity of Indian Arctiini+Amerilini genera" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5602584" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5602584/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
). In 
<collectingCountry box="[1099,1159,959,985]" name="India" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">India</collectingCountry>
, the tribe is most diverse in North-East followed by West and North-West Himalaya, Central Himalaya and Deccan Peninsula. Desert of 
<collectingCountry box="[1379,1437,995,1021]" name="India" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">India</collectingCountry>
is least diverse with single recorded species (
<figureCitation box="[655,723,1031,1058]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="12.[151,250,757,781]" captionTargetBox="[343,1237,191,725]" captionTargetId="figure-21@12.[340,1247,181,733]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 5. Distribution of Arctiini+Amerilini within the biogeographic zones/ subzones of India and among the records like ‘throughout India’, ‘North India’, and ‘India’" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5602586" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5602586/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,779,1094]" box="[199,1005,1067,1094]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,349,1067,1093]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Food plants:</emphasis>
The larvae are typical ‘wooly bears’ and are polyphagous.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
